TITLE: Apple, Amazon, Microsoft Headline Busy Earnings Week
SUMMARY: About a third of the S&P 500 and nearly half the Dow Jones Industrial Average are set to provide their quarterly updates starting Monday.

TITLE: Concert Ticket Prices Soar on Consumer Demand, Not Just Inflation
SUMMARY: Strong fan interest in better seats and experiences is prompting more aggressive pricing at the box office.

TITLE: European Lawmakers Reach Deal on New Social Media Regulations
SUMMARY: The proposed Digital Services Act aims to compel online platforms to share more information and address harmful content.

TITLE: Sanctions Strand Russia-Bound Luxury Cars
SUMMARY: Thousands of vehicles are stuck at a Belgium port as customs officials navigate what can be shipped to Russia. ‘It will take months to clear.’

TITLE: Starbucks Is Having an Identity Crisis. Can Howard Schultz Fix It?
SUMMARY: The former CEO is back for his third stint running the coffee giant. But the company is in a very different place than when he left it.

TITLE: World Governments Confront Grim Ukraine Toll
SUMMARY: The government in Kyiv has said it needs $5 billion a month in budgetary support for up to five months and roughly $600 billion for a broader rebuilding effort.

TITLE: Arizona's Dry Future Begins as Colorado River Shrinks
SUMMARY: Farms are suffering this year, and cities are expected to be hit next by the decline of one of the American Southwest’s most important sources of water.

TITLE: Global Growth Ebbs in Face of Ukraine War, China Slowdown
SUMMARY: Economic growth is slowing in large parts of the world in the face of a looming slowdown in China fueled by lockdowns and surging prices aggravated by Russia’s war in Ukraine.

TITLE: Looking for a Job? Try These Midsize Cities
SUMMARY: Austin, Nashville and Raleigh, N.C., top the Journal’s annual rankings. New York and Chicago sing the job-market blues.

TITLE: How Raleigh Rallied From the Covid-19 Pandemic
SUMMARY: The virus dealt a major blow to one of the country’s strongest regional job markets. North Carolina’s capital made a dramatic recovery.

TITLE: Pokémon Craze Returns to South Korea
SUMMARY: Young adults are embracing a nostalgic chase for the Pokémon stickers of their youth.

TITLE: Block CEO Jack Dorsey's Title Now Block Head and Chairperson
SUMMARY: The financial-services company, which says his duties won’t change, removed from its bylaws a requirement to have an officer with the title of chief executive officer and president.

TITLE: Bed Bath & Beyond's Buybuy Baby Draws Buyer Interest
SUMMARY: Suitors for the baby-gear chain include Cerberus and a SPAC chaired by Casper Sleep’s former CEO.

TITLE: Carlos Ghosn's Arrest Warrants Focus on Bonus Payments
SUMMARY: French prosecutors have zeroed in on about $16 million in payments from Renault to an Omani dealership, money they suspect ended up in companies controlled by the former auto executive and his family.

TITLE: How Goldman Sachs Is Encouraging Companies to Disclose Emissions Data
SUMMARY: The company’s asset-management arm plans to use its proxy vote to prod more companies to address data deficiencies.

TITLE: Chick-fil-A's Crazy Long Drive-Through Lines Have Santa Barbara Residents Squawking
SUMMARY: Backed-up traffic for chicken sandwiches plucks a nerve; “It’s almost like we’re in L.A. now.”

TITLE: Zappos Names Amazon Executive as Its First CMO
SUMMARY: Ginny McCormick joins from Amazon, Zappos’s parent company. Her appointment comes amid a marketing reorganization at the shoe retailer known for its customer service.
